outam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hywis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, English: variant of   Hawes   with rounding of  <i>-a-</i>.","2  English: sometimes perhaps a variant of   Huish  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hawes","meanings":["English (southern):","of Norman origin, from Anglo-Norman French and Middle English <i>Haueis</i>, <i>Hawis</i>, from an Old French form of the ancient Germanic female personal name <i>Hadewidis</i> (from <i>had-</i> ‘war’ + <i>wid-</i> with a range of possible original meanings).","variant of   Haw  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Huish","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Huish (Somerset, Wiltshire, Devon, Dorset), named with Old English <i>hīwisc</i> ‘household, family, measure of land sufficient to support a family’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":44,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":79,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":110,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Hywis was born in 1180, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Richard De Hywis I, was 22 and his mother, Mrs. Richard De Hywis, was 23. He married Ursula Greygory about 1199, in Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Cowlam, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1180–":"1180–Surnud","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1185–1257":"1185–1257","1192–Male":"1192–Surnud","1198–